diff:1618088054:1618088054:=1,75d0%0a%3c (:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c [[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a%3c [[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c [[!MorphosyntacticDiversity]]%0a%3c %0a%3c !Negative inversion%0a%3c %0a%3c :Author: ChrisC_%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Summary:''' \\%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summary]]%0a%3c %0a%3c A change in word order in negative sentences in some dialects of English%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summaryends]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Negative inversion is a phenomenon where the subject of a sentence comes after the negative auxiliary verb. This can be seen in sentences like "Can't nobody beat 'em" and "Didn't nobody get hurt or nothin'".%0a%3c %0a%3c The negative inversion construction is often used for emphasis or as an existential construction. This construction only appears when the auxiliary verb is a contraction, and the subject must be indefinite. The construction often occurs alongside negative concord, or double negatives, but it is not required.%0a%3c %0a%3c The constructions with and without the inversion are typically both well-formed in dialects that use inversion, although there are exceptions. In the West Texas dialect, the non-inverted order is only accepted if other parts of the sentence are negative: "Ain't nobody doin' nothin' wrong" and "Nobody ain't doin' nothin' wrong" are both acceptable while "Ain't none of the students done their homework" is preferred over "*None of the students ain't done their homework". Some constructions with "ain't no" in AAVE do not have a grammatical non-inverted counterpart: "Ain't no trouble to make another trip" but not "*No trouble ain't to make another trip".%0a%3c %0a%3c This construction can often be found AAVE and white English dialects in Appalachia and the south, and it is widely accepted and understood by English speakers across the US. It has also been seen in pop culture dating back to the 1990s, and has also been used by NFL players Cris Carter and James Harrison.%0a%3c %0a%3c Source: http://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/negative-inversion%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (:section: C:)%0a%3c (:Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
